Would you like me to show how to auto‑generate the “last updated” date with a simple JavaScript line so it refreshes automatically when you publish?

assistant:
That’s a nice touch: you can let the page stamp the date automatically so you don’t have to edit it each time you deploy.  

Here’s a minimal option to drop at the end of your page, right before `</body>`:

```html
<script>
  const dateEl = document.querySelector('.support-footer small');
  if (dateEl) {
    const now = new Date();
    const opts = { year: 'numeric', month: 'long' };
    dateEl.textContent = `Last updated: ${now.toLocaleDateString(undefined, opts)}`;
  }
</script>
```

It’s purposely simple—no external libraries—and displays the month and year using the browser’s locale, e.g., **“Last updated: July 2024.”**

If you ever want a fixed audit date (for documentation control), you can keep a manual string in HTML instead.  

